int, so a UUID, ULID, TypeID, Nanoid, CUID v2, KSUID, ObjectID, or TSID only adds the strategy your application imports."],[16,"Installs the current standalone binary without requiring Node.js:"],[269,"Keep familiar formats while moving to direct, portable imports."],[10,"ksuid"],[149,"KSUID"],[217,"KSUID"],[355,"KSUID"],[357,"KSUID combines a timestamp with a large random payload. Choose it for high-volume distributed systems that need chronological order and a 27-character URL-safe string."],[59,"Length of the ID, 1-256 (default: `21`)"],[69,"Length of the ID, 2-32 (default: `24`)"],[190,"Matches MongoDB's 12-byte ObjectID format."],[268,"Migrate from other libraries"],[295,"Migrate to uniku v1"],[278,"Migration is usually an import change first. Keep the stored identifier format stable, then move generation behind the new direct entry point. Every example below shows the value returned by the uniku generator."],[232,"Minified + gzipped"],[188,"MongoDB `_id` compatibility"],[363,"MongoDB-compatible 12-byte identifiers."],[352,"Most generator modules re-export all four classes, so you rarely need to import from `uniku/errors` directly. Nanoid and CUID v2, which have no binary codec, only re-export `InvalidInputError` and `UniqueIdError`."],[118,"Most generators follow the same pattern: call the generator, keep its primary value, and validate unknown input at the boundary."],[297,"Move CUID v2 to the versioned entry point"],[8,"nanoid"],[145,"Nanoid"],[183,"Nanoid"],[223,"Nanoid"],[358,"Nanoid"],[225,"Nanoid (10 chars)"],[360,"Nanoid is the compact choice for short URLs, invite codes, and session tokens. Its default alphabet is URL-safe; pass a length or options only when the boundary needs a different shape."],[191,"Native `BIGINT` storage"],[105,"No output, exit code only (`0` valid, `2` invalid)"],[86,"Node ID (`0` to `2^node-bits - 1`)"],[187,"Non-sequential, secure identifier."],[305,"Non-sequential, string-native identifiers that resist enumeration."],[226,"np